      <hedline>
        <hl1>AIDS in South Africa</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof Craig Demmer letter on Mar 19 article deplores South African Pres Thabo Mbeki's mishandling of AIDS crisis</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a native of South Africa who lost a parent to AIDS and as an AIDS researcher, I have watched with frustration as the South African government has mishandled its AIDS crisis (news article, March 19). It hard to believe that President Thabo Mbeki has sought the advice of two Americans who do not believe that H.I.V. causes AIDS.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a native of South Africa who lost a parent to AIDS and as an AIDS researcher, I have watched with frustration as the South African government has mishandled its AIDS crisis (news article, March 19). It hard to believe that President Thabo Mbeki has sought the advice of two Americans who do not believe that H.I.V. causes AIDS.</p>
        <p>Mr. Mbeki has shown his biased thinking by stopping the distribution of AZT to pregnant infected women despite the drug's proven benefits.  Further, nearly one-third of the country's AIDS budget is left unspent.</p>
        <p>I visited South Africa two months ago, and I was struck by the despair that pervades the lives of those affected by AIDS; it resembles the early years of the epidemic in the United States. What is Mr. Mbeki waiting for?</p>
        <p>CRAIG DEMMER  New York, March 20, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is an assistant professor of health services, Lehman College.</p>
      </block>
